<span id="freeTextContainer3965242798242938308">This book started really well. There was a dead patient, a daughter of a famous doctor and a friend of the protagonist was accused doing the abortion that led to the death of the patient.<br/>It was intriguing (though I am not sure that a layman could enjoy reading it uninterrupted without consulting google or dictionary) and the plot was built really well.<br/>Half through the book, I have to admit that I couldn&apos;t put it down until I finished<br/>My problem with this book is there was some unsolved mysteries </span>
  <span id="freeText3965242798242938308" style="display:none">This book started really well. There was a dead patient, a daughter of a famous doctor and a friend of the protagonist was accused doing the abortion that led to the death of the patient.<br />It was intriguing (though I am not sure that a layman could enjoy reading it uninterrupted without consulting google or dictionary) and the plot was built really well.<br />Half through the book, I have to admit that I couldn't put it down until I finished<br />My problem with this book is there was some unsolved mysteries (or maybe it is just me) at the end and there were so many characters that I constantly have to read it back and forth to figure out who is this person he's calling.<br />Overall, a solid book but not my favorite Michael Crichton's fiction (that award goes to either Sphere, State of Fear, or the Great Train Robbery).</span>
