    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3006766313" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3006766313" />
    <a title="Well Read Beard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27748422-well-read-beard"><img alt="Well Read Beard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611556111p2/27748422.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3006766313?book_show_action=true">Oct 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Well Read Beard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Well Read Beard" href="/user/show/27748422-well-read-beard">Well Read Beard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780525938026" href="/book/show/1258826.A_Case_of_Need">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27748422-well-read-beard?shelf=my-books">my-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3006766313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15441768958727984513">This is really a little higher than 3 stars when compared to the other early Crichton I have read. I liked it better than the 3 John Lange books that I have read on my quest to read all of Crichton&apos;s work. The first 50 - 100 pages were probably closer to 5 stars for me, but the deeper I got, the less I cared. The ending for me was lackluster to say the least, just didn&apos;t feel like the payoff that this book deserved.<br/><br/>This book was written in 1968, Crichton wrote it when he was 26. It is a medical </span>
  <span id="freeText15441768958727984513" style="display:none">This is really a little higher than 3 stars when compared to the other early Crichton I have read. I liked it better than the 3 John Lange books that I have read on my quest to read all of Crichton's work. The first 50 - 100 pages were probably closer to 5 stars for me, but the deeper I got, the less I cared. The ending for me was lackluster to say the least, just didn't feel like the payoff that this book deserved.<br /><br />This book was written in 1968, Crichton wrote it when he was 26. It is a medical thriller. We quickly learn that a young girl from a prominent medical family has died from what appears to be a botched abortion. A Chinese-American doctor who has a reputation of giving illegal abortions is arrested and awaiting trial. At first I kind of thought this was heading towards being some ground-breaking stuff, since the book in no way made the abortionist appear to be the villain and this was all pre Roe V Wade. It definitely felt that it was written from a perspective of leaning towards women's reproductive rights. However, while it started strong - it never really made full contact with establishing itself as ground breaking fiction in support of those rights.<br /><br />Our main character is a pathologist friend of the abortionist who believe is innocence and take it upon himself to prove it. It was an interesting look into the late 60's medical field, but in the end kind of fell flat for me.<br /><br />There are a few places in the book that come off as racist toward African Americans - using the term negro multiple times. I tried to get some context on this, trying to feel out what was socially acceptable in 1968 - but really didn't come up with a definitive answer. It just didn't read well and did not seem necessary for the narrative's situations.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15441768958727984513" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

